[src:al-pratt-baseball/1871-in-baseball] The tenth founding member, the National club of Washington, did not enter a team for the championship until 1872.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/1872-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1872 throughout the world.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/1882-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1882 throughout the world.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/1883-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1883 throughout the world.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/al-buckenberger] Buckenberger was born in Detroit, Michigan, and began his career as an infielder, and then manager for minor league teams in the Midwest.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/al-buckenberger] In 1889 he became manager of the *Columbus Solons* of the American Association for two seasons.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/al-buckenberger] After a year at the minor league Sioux City, Iowa based Sioux City Cornhuskers he joined the National League *Pittsburgh Pirates* from 1892 to 1894, and then the *St.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/al-buckenberger] He managed the *Toronto Maple Leafs*, and the *Syracuse Stars* of the Eastern League for a year each, taking Syracuse to a first place finish in 1897.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/al-buckenberger] He then managed the Eastern League *Rochester Bronchos* from 1899 to 1901, finishing first-second-first.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/al-buckenberger] Following this he rejoined the National League as manager of the *Boston Beaneaters* from 1902 to 1904.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/al-buckenberger] He returned to Rochester between 1905 and 1908.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/al-buckenberger] Al Buckenberger also served as club president at Pittsburgh.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/al-buckenberger] His biggest successes were finishing second in the American Association in 1890 and finishing second in the National League at Pittsburgh in 1893.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/al-buckenberger] After his major league days he was part of a group, together with Francis Richter, editor of Sporting Life, and fellow manager Billy Barnie that tried and failed to resurrect the American Association.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/al-buckenberger] Buckenberger died at age 56 in Syracuse, New York.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/al-pratt-baseball] A native of Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, Pratt was a Civil War veteran and baseball player.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/al-pratt-baseball] Pratt was 5'7", 140 lbs., and compiled a 12–26 record in 43 professional games as a hurler.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/al-pratt-baseball] In successive years with Cleveland, 1871–1872, Pratt hit .262 and .277 in 45 games with a total of 52 hits.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/al-pratt-baseball] Pratt managed the Portsmouth, Ohio baseball team in 1868.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/al-pratt-baseball] Afterward he was a member of the Forest City Club of Cleveland in the Professional League of Baseball Players.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/al-pratt-baseball] This was the first professional league in America.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/al-pratt-baseball] In 1880 Pratt founded the first major league club in Pittsburgh, the Alleghenys (later renamed the Pittsburgh Pirates), which joined the American Association.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/al-pratt-baseball] Pratt celebrated his 90th birthday two days before his death in Pittsburgh on November 21, 1937.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/al-pratt-baseball] He was buried, according to his request, attired in his Grand Army of the Republic uniform.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] Grammas attended Mississippi State University and signed with the Chicago White Sox in 1949.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] During his third season in the ChiSox' farm system, he was acquired by Cincinnati in 1951 and continued his minor league apprenticeship in the Reds' organization.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] Loaned to the New York Yankees' Kansas City Blues affiliate in 1953 (Cincinnati at the time lacked a Triple-A farm team), Grammas collected a career-high 179 hits and batted .307.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] He was named the American Association's All-Star shortstop.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] With Roy McMillan blocking his path in Cincinnati, the Redlegs traded Grammas in December 1953 to the St.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] Louis Cardinals; the trade marked an unusual "ping-pong" trend in Grammas' playing career, as he would bounce between Cincinnati (prior to 1954; 1956–58) and St.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] The Cardinals finally broke the pattern in June 1962 by trading Grammas to the Cubs, where he finished his career (1962–63).
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] Grammas was the Cardinals' starting shortstop in 1954, 1955 and 1959 and ranked no lower than third in fielding percentage among National League shortstops each season; he finished his career with a .969 overall fielding mark.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] He was a reserve infielder with the Redlegs and Cubs.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] All told, he appeared in 913 games played over ten MLB seasons, collecting 512 hits, with 90 doubles, ten triples, 12 home runs and 163 runs batted in.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] In 1964, Grammas began his managing career as skipper of the Cubs' Double-A affiliate, the Fort Worth Cats of the Texas League.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] Although he spent the entire year at Fort Worth, as one of the Cubs' minor league pilots he was listed as a member of the Cubs' College of Coaches that season.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] He then joined Harry Walker's staff as the third base coach for the Pittsburgh Pirates in 1965, staying on following Walker's dismissal in mid-1967.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] He began his big-league managerial career when he was asked finish out the Pirates' 1969 season after Larry Shepard was fired as the team's manager on September 26.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] Although Grammas guided the 1969 Bucs to a 4–1 finish, Danny Murtaugh took over as the team's manager in 1970.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] Grammas then returned to the Cincinnati Reds as third base coach under Sparky Anderson, spending six seasons in that post during the "Big Red Machine" era, including service on Cincinnati's 1970 and 1972 National League champions and the 1975 world champions.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] After the Milwaukee Brewers fired Del Crandall as manager near the end of the 1975 season, his place was taken on an interim basis by Harvey Kuenn.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] But following the 1975 World Series, the Brewers set their sights on Grammas as their next skipper, and signed him to a three-year contract in November 1975.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] Milwaukee Brewers President Bud Selig said that Grammas was the only manager they wanted.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] He added, "There is no question in our mind, we got the best man available.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] Grammas was, however, unable to bring the success he had seen with the Reds to Milwaukee.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] In 1976 and 1977, Grammas led the Brewers to consecutive sixth-place finishes in the American League Eastern Division, in which the Brewers finished 32 and 33 games, respectively, out of first place.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] Only the expansion 1977 Toronto Blue Jays, who lost 107 games in their inaugural season, kept the Brewers from consecutive last-place finishes under Grammas.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] A 10–5 start in 1976 led *Sports Illustrated* to publish a story praising Grammas' positive attitude and mental approach to the game.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] But the Brewers faded soon thereafter, losing 22 of their last 26 games.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] Internal signs of trouble were evident by mid-season in 1977.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] With the Brewers at 39–45, Brewers reserve first baseman Mike Hegan, who was dissatisfied with his playing time under Grammas, made national news by saying "Grammas is a nice guy, but as a manager, he makes a good third base coach".
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] Hegan added, "I think that we all expected that, when he came over here, he was going to provide motivation and leadership...but that hasn't happened".
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] After this point, the Brewers went 27–50.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] On November 21, 1977, Brewers President Bud Selig fired both Grammas and General Manager Jim Baumer.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] Grammas ended his managerial career with a record of 137–191.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] Grammas then returned to the coaching ranks and the Reds in 1978 as a member of Anderson's staff; then, after Anderson's controversial firing, Grammas coached under Bobby Cox with the 1979 Atlanta Braves.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] In mid-June of 1979, Anderson was hired as skipper of the Detroit Tigers, and during his first off-season as Detroit's manager, he added Grammas to his staff as third base coach, where Grammas served for 12 consecutive years (1980–91), including on the Tigers' 1984 world championship season.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/alex-grammas] Grammas died at his home in Birmingham, Alabama on September 13, 2019.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] The **American Association of Base Ball Clubs** (**AA**) was a professional baseball league that existed for 10 seasons from 1882 to 1891.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] Together with the National League (NL), founded in 1876, the AA participated in an early version of the World Series seven times versus the champion of the NL in an interleague championship playoff tournament.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] At the end of its run, several AA franchises joined the NL.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] After 1891, the NL existed alone, with each season's champions being awarded the Temple Cup (1894–1897).
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] During its existence, the AA was often simply referred to as "the Association" in the media, in contrast to the NL, which was sometimes called "the League".
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] It was also sometimes called the "Beer and Whiskey League".
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] The American Association (AA) distinguished itself in several ways from what it considered to be the puritanical National League (NL).
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] The new league established teams in what the NL leaders pejoratively called "river cities", including Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Louisville and St.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] Louis, with the inherent implication of lower morality or social standards in those cities.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] In contrast to the NL, the AA offered cheaper ticket prices, Sunday games and alcoholic beverages to its patrons.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] On November 8, 1881, at the Gibson House in Cincinnati, it was decided that individual teams in the league-to-be would operate their own affairs and set their own admission prices, under an agreement called the "guarantee system".
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] The NL at that time prohibited the sale of alcohol on its grounds, while the AA had no such restrictions, especially as several of its teams were backed by breweries and distilleries.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] The AA became known as "The Beer and Whiskey League", another pejorative term applied by NL owners, which did not seem to bother the fans of the Association's clubs.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] Beginning in 1884 and continuing through 1890, the champion of the AA met the champion of the NL in an early version of the World Series.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] These early Series were less organized than the modern version, with as few as three games played and as many as fifteen, and the contests of 1885 and 1890 ending in disputed ties.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] The NL won four of these Series, while the AA won only one, in 1886 when the St.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] Louis Cardinals) defeated the Chicago White Stockings (now the Chicago Cubs).
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] Over its lifetime, the AA was weakened by several factors.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] One was the tendency of some of its teams to jump to the NL.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] The consistently stronger NL was in better position to survive adverse conditions.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] Some owners of AA teams also owned a NL team.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] The most significant blow to the AA was dealt by the Players' League, a third major league formed in 1890, which siphoned off talent and gate receipts.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] In a rare historical oddity, the Brooklyn Bridegrooms (now the Los Angeles Dodgers) won the league's championship and represented the AA in the 1889 World Series, switched to the NL during the off-season, and then repeated the same feat.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] No player who spent the majority of his career in the AA is in the baseball Hall of Fame, although Bid McPhee of the Cincinnati Reds played eight of his eighteen seasons in the AA before the Reds moved to the National League.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] The living legacy of the old Association is the group of teams that came over to the National League to stay.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] The Pirates moved to the NL after the 1886 season, the Bridegrooms/Dodgers and the Cincinnati Reds after the 1889 season, and the Browns/Cardinals after the American Association folded following the 1891 season.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] Following the reorganization and contraction of the NL from 12 teams down to 8 in 1900, half of the eight surviving teams were former members of the AA.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] Several of the AA's home-field venues survived into the 1960s: The ballpark used by the 1891 Washington club evolved into Griffith Stadium; the home of the St.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] Louis Browns, Sportsman's Park; and the city block occupied by the Reds, which evolved into Crosley Field.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] Other than the clubs themselves, Crosley Field was the last physical remnant of the AA—it was the home field of the Cincinnati Reds until mid-season 1970 and was razed in April 1972.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] During the AA's existence, four clubs defected over to the NL: Allegheny City (joined NL 1887, later became the Pittsburgh Pirates), the Cleveland Spiders (joined NL 1889), the Brooklyn Bridegrooms (joined NL 1890, eventually renamed the Dodgers), and the Cincinnati Reds (joined NL 1890).
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] At the AA's demise in 1891, four additional clubs joined the NL: the St.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] Louis Browns (later the Cardinals), the Louisville Colonels, the Washington Statesmen (renamed the Senators), and the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] Therefore, from 1892 to 1899, when the NL consisted of 12 teams, 8 of them had been former AA clubs.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] All four have posted more than 10,000 all-time major-league victories.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] AA statistics are recognized by Major League Baseball (MLB), the AA being one of six leagues deemed "major" by the Special Baseball Records Committee of Major League Baseball in 1969.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] The first line is the formation of the American Association (AA) in 1882, and the second marks the end of the American Association.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] World's Championship Series championships are shown with a "•", American Association Pennants in non-World Championship Series seasons are shown with a "#", and American Association Pennant winners who tied or lost the World Championship Series are shown with a "^".
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] For the 1891 season, the Philadelphia Athletics were replaced by the Philadelphia Quakers of the Player's League.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] The 1891 Cincinnati Kelly's Killers folded during the season and were replaced by the Milwaukee Brewers.
[src:al-pratt-baseball/american-association-19th-century] All non-American Association labels not labeled "NL" (National League) or "PL" (Players' League) are minor league teams.
